The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government facing a crisis that has placed Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has put the whole eurozone at risk.
A communiqué from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected that there will be a cabinet composed in its majority by technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume the post.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "mark is now well-designed," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has fueled its debt costs at unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain the affected confidence in Italy.
Stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry up, market instability placed the performance of the Italian bonds BTP 10 years above 7 per cent, the level to which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian patronage confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti's success prospects were greatly driven by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, whom the crisis forced to leave on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are intended to have a good outcome," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the government of the majority of the technocrats who are forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Government of Monti must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added pressure to warn that Monti's failure would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He'll end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a short breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences in the euro area.
Monti has said that his government should continue until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections proceed.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his office, but the major parties insist that he should be made up only by technicians, an indication of his repairs to a process forced by financial pressure.
