The Moleskine book is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged over time.
However, the Moleskine books with the current aspect were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a book of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was responsible for launching the new product.
The bookcase is inspired by an old production technique, the skin mole (top leather), which refers to a cotton-painted that was used, inter alia, to cover the banquets.
This type of book was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he made it.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far away has been the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts both business men and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, their users are cosmopolitans, of open spirit and worship.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city center, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the increase in e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
