In August, he also launched a box with leopard caps, on account of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, schedules, handwritings, computer backgrounds... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Discouragement?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made 15 years ago is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still a lot to be done."
It should be noted that the unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (a 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% of the average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the working world and that "constitute the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mind progresses, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City pointed out that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishment "subjected to this contribution" as well as the amounts disbursed has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among the major groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities in their schedule, compared to 82 per cent of enterprises with between 100 and 199 workers.
